Purpose: Add NAT gateway note for external alert endpoints (finding L25)

[49m[38;5;9m- 23    [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Amazon SNS for alert routing.** When trajectory analysis produces an alert, it needs to reach the right person through the right channel. SNS handles fan-out to multiple subscribers: pager, EHR notification, nursing station dashboard, charge nurse summary. Topic-based routing allows different alert severities to reach different endpoints. All subscription endpoints (pager API, dashboard webhook, EHR integration) must be covered under your organization's BAA chain. An alert containing vital signs and patient identifiers is PHI regardless of the delivery channel.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SNS for alert routing.** When trajectory analysis produces an alert, it needs to reach the right person through the right channel. SNS handles fan-out to multiple subscribers: pager, EHR notification, nursing station dashboard, charge nurse summary. Topic-based routing allows different alert severities to reach different endpoints. All subscription endpoints (pager API, dashboard webhook, EHR integration) must be covered under your organization's BAA chain. An alert containing vital signs and patient identifiers is PHI regardless of the delivery channel. If alert delivery targets external endpoints (a pager vendor API, for example), configure a NAT gateway in a controlled private subnet with outbound security group rules limited to the vendor's published IP ranges. Prefer VPC-internal integrations via PrivateLink wherever possible to avoid PHI egress to the public internet entirely. The VPC prerequisite row below specifies "no NAT gateway" for the processing workloads; the NAT gateway exception applies only to the narrow alert-delivery path, in a dedicated subnet with its own restricted security group.
